Remarks.

Adetus croton


sp. nov.

is similar to 

A. bacillarius
Bates, 1885

(
Figs. 14, 16, 18, 20, 24
), and has been confused with it. However, the new species differs from it as follows: meso- (
Fig. 17
) and metatibiae (
Fig. 19
) of males proportionally shorter and conical, especially metatibiae; mesotibiae not excavated dorsally on posterior third, and without fringe of thick and erect setae (
Fig. 17
); pronotum not longitudinally sulcate on each side of central area (
Figs. 6, 10, 13
); elytra with two wide transverse white pubescent bands (sometimes, the anterior one ill-formed) (
Figs. 6, 10, 13
); lower eye lobes (
Fig. 9
) smaller. In 

A. bacillarius

, the meso- (
Fig. 18
) and metatibiae (
Fig. 20
) of males proportionally longer and not conical, mesotibiae (
Fig. 18
) of males excavated dorsally on posterior third, and with fringe of thick and erect setae (
Fig. 18
), pronotum longitudinally sulcate on each side of central area (sometimes slightly distinct, especially depending on the angle of view) (
Figs. 14, 24
), elytra without transverse white pubescent bands (
Figs. 14, 24
), and lower eye lobes (
Fig. 16
) larger. The new species is also similar to 

A. modestus
Melzer, 1934

(
Figs. 15, 21
), but differs by the prothorax slightly slender and elongate (
Figs. 6, 10, 13
), metatibiae in male proportionally shorter and conical (
Fig. 19
), and antennomeres from IV proportionally shorter and stouter (
Figs. 6, 10, 13
). In 

A. modestus

, the prothorax is slightly stouter and shorter (
Fig. 15
), metatibiae in male are proportionally longer and not conical (
Fig. 21
), and antennomeres from IV proportionally slender and longer (
Fig. 15
). The new species also can be separated from 

A. brousii
(Horn, 1880)

(
Fig. 22
), and 

A. binotatus
(Thomson, 1868)

(
Fig. 23
), especially by the shape of the metatibiae (
Fig. 19
).
